            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dmitri Evans\u2019s story begins with a name chosen by his adoptive father, a Sacramento high school English teacher with a love for Russian literature. Born in Seoul and adopted at six months old, Dmitri was raised in a loving, academically-minded caucasian household. His upbringing was thoroughly American, filled with Little League, suburban cul-de-sacs, and summer road trips. While he always knew he was adopted, the cultural disconnect was a quiet, low-humming frequency in the background of his life.\n\nHe moved to San Francisco for college, enrolling in Business Administration at SF State. He was sharp and capable but lacked passion for the coursework. The true turning point came during his sophomore year when his father suffered a major heart attack. Dmitri left school to work full-time, taking a mailroom job at a biotech consulting firm to help his parents with the mounting bills. He never went back to finish his degree.\n\nWhat Dmitri lacked in formal education, he made up for with an uncanny talent for logistics and a relentless work ethic. He saw inefficiencies others missed and quietly fixed them. Over two decades, he climbed the internal ladder: from mailroom clerk to office coordinator, to project assistant, and finally to Operations Manager. He is the organizational backbone of the firm, the one who ensures the brilliant scientists and consultants have a seamless environment in which to work.\n\nNow 42, Dmitri\u2019s life is a study in routine and quiet contentment. He lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood he loves for its fog, cultural mix, and proximity to Golden Gate Park. His daily 6.5-mile commute to SoMa on the 5R Fulton bus is his time to decompress with podcasts on history or economics. He\u2019s been on many dates but has never found a lasting partnership, finding solace instead in a small, loyal circle of friends he meets for weekly trivia at a neighborhood pub.\n\nHis greatest aspiration isn't a new job title or a bigger salary. Dmitri dreams of taking a six-week trip to South Korea. It\u2019s not about finding his birth family, but about finally connecting with the culture he sees in the mirror every day\u2014to walk the streets of Seoul, understand the language, and perhaps, reconcile the man named Dmitri with the face of a man born a world away."
        },
